    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-29T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-29T06:00:00-05:00" n="812"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d812">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867.24/312: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-29T14:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 29, 1942—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>499. My 434, May 16, 3 p.m.<note n="26" xml:id="d812fn26">Not printed.</note>
                    Secretary General of Foreign Office told me informally last night that Council
                    of Ministers has given its formal approval to new procedure with regard to
                    furnishing of supplies to Turkey and that he expected to transmit written notice
                    to foregoing effect to American and British Embassies prior to June 3d.</p>
                <p>Immediately upon receipt of formal notification from Ministry of Foreign Affairs
                    that new procedure has been accepted by Turk Government and unless instructed by
                    Department to contrary British-American Coordination Committee will commence to
                    function in cooperation with Turk Coordination Committee.</p>
                <p>I anticipate telegraphing Department next week Embassy’s recommendations
                    concerning several subjects which in my opinion should be considered in any
                    master lend-lease negotiations Department may inaugurate.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
